Introduction

In the modern academic and professional landscape, digital literacy is a fundamental skill that goes beyond basic computer usage. This project follows my journey as a newly selected Student Digital Ambassador, tasked with helping my peers navigate professional online profiling, safe communication, and technical collaboration. By completing five distinct modules, I have developed a comprehensive portfolio that demonstrates my ability to use essential digital tools responsibly.
This report documents the creation of visual resources, the establishment of a professional digital footprint, technical practice on coding platforms, and the promotion of cybersecurity awareness within our college community.


Task 1 Write-up: Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic

For this task, I designed a one-page visual infographic using Canva to educate my batchmates on the core pillars of digital literacy.
The design highlights three primary areas: the definition of digital literacy, essential tools for students and safe internet practices, including the use of the National Cyber Crime Helpline.
I chose a clean, professional blue-and-white theme to ensure readability and authority. One thing I found particularly interesting was the challenge of condensing complex information like the various facets of professional online presence into a single, scannable visual format.
One thing I found challenging organizing a large amount of information without making the poster look cluttered.
This exercise taught me that effective digital communication relies as much on visual hierarchy and design as it does on the text itself, making it a vital skill for any Digital Ambassador.

Task 2 Write-up: Build Your Student Digital Portfolio

Building a professional digital presence is a requirement in today's competitive environment. I established foundational profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle to serve as my professional base.
On GitHub, I created a profile to master AI and ML concepts. It is mainly used for version control and collaboration.
On LinkedIn, I updated my education section to reflect my current degree at VIT Bhopal University. LinkedIn will serve as my primary networking tool, while GitHub and Kaggle will act as living repositories for my technical projects and data science experiment.
Kaggle provides dataset, notebooks, and competitions that help student improve their practical skills. I choose Kaggle because it gives hands on experience in ML.
Over the next four years, I plan to use these platforms to document my growth, share open source contributions, and connect with industry leaders for internship opportunities. This module helped me realize that a digital portfolio is not static; it is a long term asset that requires consistent maintenance.

Task 3 Write-up: Coding & Collaboration Platforms

Part-A

To guide my peers toward effective collaboration tools, I explored both technical and cloud-based platforms. I completed the "Solve Me First" Python challenge on Hacker Rank, which helped me practice basic problem-solving logic and familiarize myself with automated evaluation environments.

Part-B

Google forms is a tool for creating surveys, quizzes and feedback. I created a Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz using Google Forms, featuring five questions to test peer knowledge on digital safety and professional etiquette. This process demonstrated the power of cloud collaboration; the linked Google Sheet allows for real-time tracking of responses, which is invaluable for any technical event coordinator. These tools are essential for my academic journey as they facilitate organized data collection and continuous technical skill-building.

Task 4 Write-up: Professional Email & Etiquette

Part-A Write two professional mails
Professional communication is a cornerstone of digital literacy. I drafted two professional emails-one requesting a deadline extension from a professor and another expressing interest in a summer internship. These drafts emphasize clarity, proper salutations, and a respectful tone.
Part-B
I also developed a Social Media Do’s and Don’ts checklist to encourage responsible online behaviour.
A key learning from this task is that poor digital communication can lead to significant real-world misunderstandings. For instance, an informally phrased email to an internship coordinator might be interpreted as a lack of professional discipline, potentially closing doors to future opportunities. Learning to match the tone of communication to the recipient is a skill I will continue to emphasize to my peers

Task 5 Write-up: Cybercrime Awareness & Prevention

Researching UPI or Online Payment Fraud for my case study was eye opening. I was surprised to learn how easily scammers use social engineering and "spoofed" payment confirmation screens to deceive even tech-savvy users. This research highlighted that human psychology, rather than technical flaws, is often the weakest link in cybersecurity.
As a direct result, I have changed my personal habit of scanning random QR codes without verification and now ensure that I only use official UPI apps for every transaction. My prevention checklist now includes the National Cyber Crime Helpline (1930), which I believe every student should have saved in their contacts. As a Digital Ambassador, I feel more prepared to help my batchmates recognize these threats before they become victims.
This research has made me more aware , responsible , and digitally safe.

Conclusion

This project has significantly broadened my understanding of what it means to be digitally literate in a professional context. I have moved beyond being a mere consumer of technology to becoming a creator and a responsible communicator. By organizing these tasks into a permanent GitHub repository, I have not only fulfilled my course requirements but also established a digital foundation that will support my career in AI and ML for years to come.

